### Class Inheritance

Inheritance allows a class to derive properties and methods from another class.

### Basic Inheritance

```typescript
class Animal {
  constructor(public name: string) {}

  move(distance: number = 0): void {
    console.log(`${this.name} moved ${distance}m`);
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  bark(): void {
    console.log("Woof!");
  }
}

const dog = new Dog("Buddy");
dog.move(10); // Inherited from Animal
dog.bark(); // Dog's own method
```

### Method Overriding

```typescript
class Animal {
  makeSound(): string {
    return "Some sound";
  }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
  makeSound(): string {
    return "Meow";
  }
}
```

### super Keyword

```typescript
class Animal {
  constructor(public name: string) {}

  describe(): string {
    return `Animal: ${this.name}`;
  }
}

class Bird extends Animal {
  constructor(name: string, public wingspan: number) {
    super(name);
  }

  describe(): string {
    return `${super.describe()}, Wingspan: ${this.wingspan}cm`;
  }
}
```

### Protected Members

```typescript
class Base {
  protected secret: string = "hidden";
  private verySecret: string = "very hidden";
}

class Derived extends Base {
  reveal(): string {
    return this.secret; // OK: protected is accessible
    // return this.verySecret; // Error: private
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** JavaScript supports single inheritance — a class can extend only one other class.

codeExample:
class Vehicle {
  constructor(
    public make: string,
    public model: string,
    protected year: number
  ) {}

  getInfo(): string {
    return `${this.make} ${this.model} (${this.year})`;
  }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
  constructor(
    make: string,
    model: string,
    year: number,
    public doors: number
  ) {
    super(make, model, year);
  }

  getInfo(): string {
    return `${super.getInfo()}, ${this.doors} doors`;
  }
}

const myCar = new Car("Toyota", "Camry", 2024, 4);
console.log(myCar.getInfo());
